</m:mtd>
</m:mtr>
</m:mtable>
</m:math>
</equation></para>
<para id="element-44">
The angular acceleration is measured in “
<m:math>
<m:mi> rad </m:mi>
<m:mo> / </m:mo>
<m:msup>
<m:mi> s </m:mi>
<m:mn> 2 </m:mn>
</m:msup>
</m:math>
”. It is important to emphasize here that this angular acceleration is associated with the change in angular speed (ω) i.e. change in the linear speed of the particle (v = ωr)  - not associated with the change in the direction of the linear velocity (<term>v</term>). In the case of uniform circular motion, ω = constant, hence angular acceleration is zero.
</para>
</section>


